Remmia. This list should be memorized as it stands, though not all of the verbs are to be used immediately. As the Eng- lish renderings are taken up, it will be found that they give little or no clue to the Latin construction. Only constant vigilance, there· fore, will insure against error in connection with the use of verbs of this class.

Nom. Ratus belongs to a small group of deponent perfect participles used loosely with the force of presents. The rather frequent occurrence. of these participles is doubtless one of the reasons why the nominative forms of present participles are ern- ployed so infrequently in Latin (cf. footnote 16 on Exercise III).
